{
  "style": "IEEE",
  "texts": [
    "The flexibility of DNNs, which allows them to learn from data without requiring prior assumptions, offers substantial advantages when working with real-time time series data [12].",
    "With the growing research interest in deep learning, neural network architectures specifically designed for sequential data, such as recurrent neural networks (RNNs) [9] and their variants, as well as Transformer models [13], have demonstrated significant improvements in TSF by capturing long-term temporal dependencies and learning complex non-linear functions.",
    "These models excel in both point forecasting and multi-horizon prediction, as they effectively capture intricate patterns in the data, enabling better adaptation to sudden changes and outliers.",
    "Furthermore, ensemble and hybrid models, which integrate multiple forecasting methods, have been proposed to further improve the accuracy of predicting extreme events [14].While progress has been made, accurately predicting rare and extreme occurrences in time series data continues to be a complex and evolving field of study [4].",
    "This underscores the importance of developing tailored methods specifically designed to forecast time series that include unusual or extreme data points."
  ],
